📌 Concept Explanation

A Key Pair in AWS consists of:

Public Key → Stored securely in AWS
Private Key → Stored locally by the administrator

When an EC2 instance is launched, AWS injects the public key into the instance. The administrator then uses the corresponding private key to authenticate securely via SSH.

            AWS
      ┌──────────────┐
      │ Public Key   │
      └──────┬───────┘
             │
      Launch EC2 Instance
             │
             ▼
      ┌──────────────┐
      │ EC2 Instance │
      └──────┬───────┘
             ▲
             │ SSH Authentication
             │
      ┌──────────────┐
      │ Private Key  │
      │ (Local PC)   │
      └──────────────┘
Why Key Pairs Matter

Unlike traditional servers that use usernames and passwords, cloud environments rely heavily on SSH key-based authentication because it provides:

Stronger security than passwords
Protection against brute-force attacks
Secure automation for DevOps workflows
Authentication without transmitting passwords over the network

This is why AWS requires a key pair when launching most Linux EC2 instances.

