Implementation
Step 1: Define the AWS Provider
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

This tells Terraform which cloud provider to interact with and the AWS region where resources will be created.

Step 2: Create the Key Pair Resource
resource "aws_key_pair" "devops_kp" {
  key_name   = "devops-kp"
  public_key = file("~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub")
}
Explanation
aws_key_pair → Terraform resource for AWS EC2 key pairs
key_name → Name displayed in the AWS Console
public_key → Reads the local public key file and uploads it to AWS

Note: Terraform uploads only the public key. Your private key remains on your local machine and should never be committed to version control.

Step 3: Initialize Terraform
terraform init

This downloads the AWS provider plugin and initializes the working directory.

Step 4: Validate Configuration
terraform validate

This checks the configuration for syntax errors before deployment.

Step 5: Preview Infrastructure
terraform plan

This generates an execution plan showing what Terraform intends to create without making changes.

Step 6: Deploy Infrastructure
terraform apply

Type:

yes

Terraform creates the AWS Key Pair.

Step 7: Verify Deployment

Confirm the resource exists:

terraform state list

Expected output:

aws_key_pair.devops_kp

You can also verify the key pair in the AWS Management Console under:

EC2 → Network & Security → Key Pairs

